    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-08-09T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-08-09T22:00:00-05:00" n="825"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d825">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">821.76/8–944: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bogotá</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-08-09T22:00:00-05:00"
                            >August 9, 1944—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 9—5:23 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1400. Following is gist of reply which has been made by Colombian communications
                    authorities to Embassy’s representations concerning interference referred to in
                    Department’s 943 of July 31.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“This office is studying problem in order to find prompt solution by
                        assigning new frequencies to Cúcuta and Cali stations. Although it is
                        difficult at present to change frequencies due to congestion in bands
                        affected and because such stations have been using these frequencies since
                        1939 this office hopes that the interference now being experienced by
                        AT&amp;T stations is not very serious since Colombian stations in question
                        use only 1000 watts and since no other case of interference from them has
                        arisen during their 5 years of service in their present frequencies.”</p>
                </quote>
                <p>Further developments will be reported promptly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
